 likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choriocarcinoma","Embryonal carcinoma","Seminoma","Teratoma","Yolk sac tumour"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of Schiller-Duval bodies is pathognomonic for \u003Cstrong\u003Eyolk sac tumour\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as endodermal sinus tumour. These characteristic structures appear as perivascular arrangements that resemble primitive glomeruli under microscopy. These rare tumours usually occur in young children, but can be found at other ages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows syncytiotrophoblasts and cytotrophoblasts on histology. \u003Cstrong\u003ESeminoma\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates sheets of uniform cells with clear cytoplasm and prominent nucleoli. \u003Cstrong\u003ETeratoma\u003C/strong\u003E contains tissue from all three germ cell layers and shows various degrees of differentiation. \u003Cstrong\u003EEmbryonal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows poorly differentiated cells with high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratios arranged in sheets or glands.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schiller-Duval bodies are pathognomonic histological features of yolk sac tumours of the testis","Yolk sac tumours are a type of non-seminomatous germ cell tumour that typically occurs in young children","Schiller-Duval bodies appear as perivascular structures resembling primitive glomeruli under microscopy"],"references":["Boccellino M, Vanacore D, Zappavigna S, Cavaliere C, Rossetti S, D\u0027Aniello C, Chieffi P, Amler E, Buonerba C, Di Lorenzo G, Di Franco R, Izzo A, Piscitelli R, Iovane G, Muto P, Botti G, Perdon\u00e0 S, Caraglia M, Facchini G. Testicular cancer from diagnosis to epigenetic factors. Oncotarget. 2017 Sep 18;8(61):104654-104663. doi: 10.18632/oncotarget.20992. PMID: 29262668; PMCID: PMC5732834","Chung P, Warde P. Testicular cancer: germ cell tumours. 